{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "updatedAt": "2026-06-22T17:53:16.029Z",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "At its core, every large language model is a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "language model",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": a system trained to assign probabilities to sequences of tokens. By learning to predict what token comes next, the model internalizes grammar, facts, reasoning patterns, and conversational structure. Agent behavior — planning, tool selection, response generation — emerges from this next-token prediction objective applied at scale."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What it is"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Language modeling estimates P(token_t | token_1, ..., token_{t-1}) — the probability of each next token given prior context. Autoregressive models generate text one token at a time, sampling or greedily selecting from the predicted distribution. Training maximizes log-likelihood of token sequences in a large corpus, which implicitly teaches syntax, semantics, and world knowledge."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why it matters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Agents are language models wrapped in control logic. Understanding language modeling explains why models hallucinate ( plausible continuations ≠ verified truth), why temperature affects creativity, why longer context enables multi-step reasoning in a single thread, and why fine-tuning on demonstrations changes behavior (it shifts conditional probabilities toward desired continuations)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Benefits"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Unified training objective",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — one loss function scales to trillion-token corpora"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Emergent capabilities",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — reasoning and coding arise from scale without task-specific heads"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Flexible inference",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — same model generates, classifies (via prompting), and transforms text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Foundation for agents",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — tool use and planning are learned as conditional text patterns"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Trade-offs"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Optimizes plausibility, not truth — confident false statements are likely continuations"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Autoregressive generation is sequential — latency grows with output length"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Long-range dependencies require large context windows and attention compute"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Training data biases become conditional generation biases"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "How it works"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Training: feed token sequence into model, predict next token at each position, compute cross-entropy loss against actual next tokens, backpropagate."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\n\n# Illustrative next-token logits for a tiny vocabulary\nlogits = torch.tensor([2.0, 1.0, 0.1, -1.0])  # scores for 4 tokens\ntargets = torch.tensor(0)  # correct next token is index 0\n\nloss = F.cross_entropy(logits.unsqueeze(0), targets.unsqueeze(0))\nprobs = F.softmax(logits, dim=0)\nprint(\"Probs:\", probs.tolist())\nprint(\"Loss:\", loss.item())"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Inference: model outputs logits over vocabulary; apply temperature, top-p, or greedy selection to pick next token; append to context; repeat until stop condition."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def sample_next_token(logits, temperature=1.0):\n    scaled = logits / max(temperature, 1e-8)\n    probs = F.softmax(scaled, dim=-1)\n    return torch.multinomial(probs, num_samples=1).item()"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When to use it"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Language modeling concepts apply to every agent LLM call — generation, logprob-based classification, constrained decoding, and confidence estimation. Use explicit language model terminology when reading papers, configuring sampling parameters, or designing evals based on perplexity."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Examples"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Given context \"The capital of France is\", the model assigns highest probability to \" Paris\". Given \"The API returns status code 4\", it may assign probability to \"04\", \"00\", \"29\" depending on training data — explaining why agents need validation for structured outputs."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Real-world example"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "An agent uses logprobs from the language model head to detect uncertainty: when the top token for a classification label has logprob below -1.0, the agent escalates to a human. This leverages the language model's calibrated(ish) probability surface without a separate classifier."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Common mistakes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Treating LLM outputs as factual because they are fluent (high-probability continuations)"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Ignoring that instruction tuning reshapes but does not replace the language modeling objective"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Confusing perplexity improvements with task-specific agent accuracy"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Best practices"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Use logprobs and temperature consciously for agent decision thresholds"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Validate structured outputs independently of generation fluency"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Design prompts as context that steers conditional token distributions"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Monitor output length — autoregressive cost scales linearly with generated tokens"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Comparison with alternatives"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Masked language modeling (BERT-style) predicts masked tokens bidirectionally — good for encoding, not generation. Autoregressive language modeling (GPT-style) predicts left-to-right — the foundation for generative agents. Sequence-to-sequence models add explicit encoder-decoder structure; modern agents largely use decoder-only autoregressive models."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mental model"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Language modeling is ultra-fast autocomplete with a PhD — at each step the model asks \"what word would best continue this text?\" and agents steer that question with prompts and tools."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Key takeaways"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "LLMs are autoregressive language models trained to predict next tokens"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Agent capabilities emerge from scaled next-token prediction plus instruction tuning"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Fluency reflects high probability, not guaranteed correctness"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Sampling parameters control how the model explores its conditional distributions"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
